The goal of the treatment for pyruvate dehydrogenase complex (PDC) deficiency is to stimulate the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex to produce as much energy as possible. This can prevent immediate worsening of the disease.[2851][2852] Treatment options typically include supplementing <a href="https://www.britannica.com/science/cofactor">cofactors</a> including <a href="https://ods.od.nih.gov/factsheets/Carnitine-HealthProfessional/">carnitine</a>, <a href="https://medlineplus.gov/druginfo/natural/965.html">thiamine</a>, and <a href="http://lpi.oregonstate.edu/mic/dietary-factors/lipoic-acid">lipoic acid</a>. These are substances in the body that help the chemical reactions in the cells occur.[2851] Certain genetic changes (<a href="https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/primer/mutationsanddisorders/genemutation">mutations</a> or pathogenic variants) that cause PDC deficiency may be more responsive to thiamine treatment than others.[14378]<br />
<br />
A medication called <a href="https://www.cancer.gov/publications/dictionaries/cancer-drug/def/sodium-dichloroacetate">dichloroacetate</a> may help treat some people with PDC deficiency. Doctors may also recommend a diet that is high in fats and low in <a href="https://medlineplus.gov/carbohydrates.html">carbohydrates</a> (<a href="https://www.ruled.me/guide-keto-diet/">ketogenic diet</a>). This can help prevent lactic acidosis but typically does not stop neurological symptoms.[2851] Medications to help prevent <a href="https://medlineplus.gov/seizures.html">seizures</a> may be recommended for some people with PDC deficiency.[14379]&nbsp;
